# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-challenger-1970
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] The core business of the AMAG Group is the company AMAG Automobil- und Motoren AG founded in 1945 by Walter Haefner and based in Zurich.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] On 29 April 1948, the company signed an import agreement with Volkswagen, and then again with Porsche in 1951, both of which continue to form the basis of the car import business operated by AMAG.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] In May 2008, AMAG ceased importing Porsche vehicles, as the subsidiary Porsche Swiss Ltd asserted its right to the trade.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] However, AMAG remains the Porsche brand's biggest retail partner and, according to information provided by the company itself, is the largest Porsche retail organisation in Switzerland with 6 sales and service locations and the fourth-largest Porsche dealer in the world.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] From 1949-72, assembly of different types of vehicles took place at "Automontage Schinznach AG" in Schinznach Bad for Chrysler Corporation (Chrysler, DeSoto, Dodge, and Plymouth), Standard, Studebaker, and VW (Karmann-Ghia).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] Since 2018, AMAG has been a co-owner and, since 2025, the majority owner of autoSense, the solution for digital vehicle networking and charging solutions, and since 2019 it has been offering a car subscription model with Clyde.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] Clyde now focuses on subscriptions for electric vehicles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] As an absolute novelty, the subscription price also includes the cost of charging at home and on the road.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] It is also a partner in the Swiss Startup Factory.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] Since January 2021, *mobilog AG* has been taking over AMAG's logistics tasks.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] AMAG is one of the founding members of the industry association *Swiss Alliance for Collaborative Mobility* (CHACOMO).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] In 2022, the AMAG Group acquired the energy services company Helion and founded Helion Energy AG.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] Since 2023, it has held a stake in the Danish company Holo A/S, an operator of autonomous vehicle fleets.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] As of the new vehicle registrations in 2025, the market shares of the key AMAG brands are as follows: Volkswagen: 11.0%, ŠKODA: 9.5% Audi: 7.4%, and Seat/Cupra: 4.2%.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] Eva Maria Bucher-Haefner, the daughter of AMAG founder Walter Haefner, who died in 2012, sold her 50% share to her brother in December 2018 and stepped down from the boards of directors of the AMAG Group companies.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] The AMAG Group is therefore owned solely by Martin Haefner.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] The company's former headquarters at Zurich's Utoquai is owned by Eva Maria Bucher-Haefner; the AMAG garage and dealership situated on the ground floor operate there as tenants.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] Until 2013, the company logo symbolised an Auto Union racing car Type A driving towards the viewer.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] The vehicle's body formed the centre, with the front tyres and their drum brakes and axes to the left and right.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] In September 2013, AMAG completely overhauled its branding and thus also its logo.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/amag-automobil-und-motoren] The company now uses plain lettering as its logo.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/american-motors-corporation-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] The company, which was also the first truckmaker in Turkey, ceased production in 2011.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] Askam was founded in 1962 as a joint venture with 60% ownership by Chrysler, the company originally traded under the "Chrysler Sanayi A.Ş." name.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] Production of trucks started in 1964 under the Chrysler, Fargo, Desoto, and Dodge brand names.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] Most of the models built utilized a cab and front end developed by Chrysler specifically for manufacture in developing countries.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] This cab, in modified form, continued to be used by Askam until its bankruptcy.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] In 1978, Chrysler sold its share to the local partners and then owners, Tatko, Çiftçiler & Ruşensad.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] Askam continued production under the Chrysler's license agreement.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] Most of Askam's products used Perkins diesel engines.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] After an agreement signed with Japanese Hino Motors in 1991, Askam started production of mini trucks branded "Hino".
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] When Daimler-Benz and Chrysler merged operations in 1998, Askam changed its name to "Askam Kamyon Imalat ve Ticaret AŞ" in 2002 and continued to produce its products under the Fargo and Desoto brands.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] Askam produced a variety of Fargo and Desoto heavy and light trucks of its own designs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] The numerical portion of the model names (AS250, AS700, AS950) stand for the payload in metric tonnes (e.g.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] In 2003, Çiftçiler Holding became the only owner of the company after acquiring Tatko and Ruşensad shares.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] The last trucks were produced in 2011, and attempts were made to sell or revive the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/askam-trucks] While trying to buy Askam from Renault Trucks and Temsa, cooperation with the Chinese truck manufacturer Sinotruk came to the forefront; however, none of the opportunities materialized.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Formula Vee was announced in 1960 by the Sports Car Club of America (SCCA) and Volkswagen of America.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Caldwell designed the Caldwell D-1 based on a Cooper formula car chassis and built it with help from friends.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The D-1 was received well by the public and Caldwell decided to produce the car.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The D-1 was produced in 1964 and 1965 in different variants.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] In 1964 the SCCA included the Formula Vee class in the SCCA National Championship Runoffs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Autodynamics, along with Formcar and Zink Cars, were the pioneers of the series.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Lewis Kerr won the inaugural SCCA National Championship Runoffs for Formula Vee in a Formcar, and Roger Barr finished second.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Autodynamics produced a total of 478 Formula Vees.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] It took Autodynamics until 1972 to win a National Championship in Formula Vee.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Dave Weitzenhof beat a field with many Zink and Lynx chassis.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Caldwell's final FV design, the D-13, had a *zero-roll-stiffness* rear suspension and aerodynamic body that dominated SCCA National Races for several years.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] However, frequently repeated claims that Reeves Callaway won the National Championship in a D-13 in 1973 are exaggerated.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Callaway did finish the race in first place, but was subsequently disqualified for illegal engine modifications.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The Caldwell D-9 was the first Formula Ford chassis made in the U.S.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] It followed the chassis and suspension design of the British Merlin FF.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Introduced for the 1969 season, a D-9 piloted by Skip Barber won the SCCA North East Division championship as well as the National Championship Runoffs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] A Caldwell D-9 also won the inaugural race sanctioned by the IMSA.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] At Pocono Raceway Formula Ford cars ran on the 5/8-mile oval track for 200 laps.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Caldwell driver Jim Clarke was declared the winner.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] David Loring won many FF races in a D-9, including the Ontario and Canadian Formula Ford series, as well as the IMSA Pro Series.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] In 1967 Autodynamics launched the Caldwell D7 built to Group 7 rules to enter the 1967 Can-Am season.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Sam Posey again was the main driver for the team with Brett Lunger and Ray Caldwell driving selected rounds.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The D7 made its debut at Road America where it retired with a broken half shaft.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] At Mosport Park Posey finished twelfth, the best result of the season.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] With Posey scoring a podium at Stardust International Raceway.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The D7 returned in 1968 where it finished fourth at Autódromo Hermanos Rodríguez, the first round of the 1968 United States Road Racing Championship.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The following round, at Riverside Raceway, Posey improved to third, scoring the cars only podium finish.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Eventually, Posey's team abandoned the D-7 for a more conventional Lola T-160 CanAm chassis.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Autodynamics had a short lived Formula 5000 project with the Caldwell D8, another unusual live axle racing design.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Lunger and Posey were the drivers for the one off project.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Lunger crashed the first chassis during a test, the races were done with a second chassis.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] In the pro-series Posey scored the best result, a seventh place at Lime Rock Park.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Sam Posey went on to earn the runner-up title twice in the U.S.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] In 1972, he did not run the complete eight-race series but still placed second three times and third twice.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Chrysler entered the Trans-Am Series with their two pony car types the Plymouth 'Cuda and the Dodge Challenger.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The 'Cudas were entered by Dan Gurneys All American Racers as a factory funded effort.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] AAR performed all the initial engineering, modification and extensive fabrication of the body-in-white (no VIN Numbers for street use) uni-bodies, fenders, k-frame and "other" components (progress of chassis development and completion dated letter from AAR/Bob R.L.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Tarozzi to Pete Hutchinson at Chrysler dated 2/2/1970 confirms).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] AAR sent the later production line body-in-white chasses out to have them stripped of all paint (receipt from Superior Paint Stripping Inc.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The Cuda and Challenger chasses were sent to Aerochem, Inc in Orange, Ca for "chemmilling of .006-.007 in. per surface (see Aerochem invoice dated 11/18/69 confirms).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Sam Posey was the full-time driver for the first Dodge Challenger.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] It has been stated that the first chassis was left in the acid too long weakening the roof and structural integrity of the car (see Chapter 6, page 135 Mudge Pond Express confirms).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The car required multiple chassis repairs between races. until AAR came up with a solution to re-enforce the torsion bar areas in the floor that were tearing under hard braking and cornering forces (photos of the floor and cage re-enforcements from Chrysler Archives confirms).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] All chassis, braking, suspension and steering components were fabricated by AAR and sent to Caldwell (letter from Carroll Smith-Autodynamics Product Engineer letter to Bruce Junor at AAR dated 6/19/1979 confirms).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The de-stroked 340 ci based engine to 305ci Dodge V8 engines (built by Keith Black) proved unreliable due to factory lifter angles and push rod length design not conducive to high rpm racing requirements causing multiple retirements.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Posey scored three podium finishes during the season accumulating all the team's points.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] During the last two races, at Seattle and Riverside, a second car was entered.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] A Mid-Season decision by Chrysler to not return in 1971 killed off the efforts (internal memorandum from Max Muhlman announcing a reorganization due to Chrysler funding cutbacks dated 5/21/1970 and Chrysler letter from Pete Hutchinson to Bruce Junor at AAR dated 10/13/1970 confirms).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Ford and Chevrolet also canceled their racing programs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] Autodynamics eventually built 3 Challengers and Black provided 12 engines during the season.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The cancellation led to a financial crisis for Autodynamics which was forced to reorganize under Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] In 1972, Caldwell and entrepreneur Bob MacArthur launched an electric passenger car development program in an attempt to save the company.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/autodynamics-race-car-manufacturer] The firm converted a number of gasoline production cars to run on electric motors, but lead-acid battery technology was too heavy and inefficient for widespread acceptance.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The **Dodge Challenger** is an automobile produced by American automobile manufacturer Dodge.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The first use of the Challenger name by Dodge was in 1959 for marketing a "value version" of the full-sized Coronet Silver Challenger.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] From model years 1970 to 1974, the first generation Dodge Challenger pony car was built using the Chrysler E platform in hardtop and convertible body styles sharing major components with the Plymouth Barracuda.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Introduced in the autumn of 1969 for the 1970 model year, the Challenger was one of two Chrysler E-body cars, the other being the slightly smaller Plymouth Barracuda.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Positioned to compete against the Mercury Cougar and Pontiac Firebird in the upper end of the pony car market segment, it was "a rather late response" to the Ford Mustang, which debuted in April 1964.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Even so, Chrysler intended the new Challenger as the most potent pony car ever, and like the less expensive Barracuda, it was available in a staggering number of trim and option levels, and with virtually every engine in Chrysler's inventory.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The Challenger's longer wheelbase, larger dimensions, and more luxurious interior were prompted by the launch of the 1967 Mercury Cougar, likewise, a bigger, more luxurious, and more expensive pony car aimed at affluent young American buyers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The 110 in (2,800 mm) wheelbase was 2 in (51 mm) longer than the Barracuda's, and the Dodge differed substantially in its sheet metal, much as the Cougar differed from the shorter-wheelbase Mustang.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Air conditioning and a rear window defogger were optional.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] With 1971 being the sole exception, the front ends of both cars differed from each other in that the Challenger had four headlights and the Barracuda had only two; a trend replicated by offerings from Chrysler's rivals.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The exterior design was penned by Carl Cameron, who was also responsible for the exterior designs of the 1966 Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Cameron based the 1970 Challenger grille on an older sketch of a stillborn 1966 Charger prototype that was to have a turbine engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The pony car segment was already declining by the time the Challenger arrived.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Sales fell dramatically after 1970, and though sales rose for the 1973 model year with over 27,800 cars being sold, Challenger production ceased midway through the 1974 model year.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] A total of 165,437 first-generation Challengers were sold.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] For its introductory model year the Challenger was available in two series, Challenger and Challenger R/T, and three models, two-door hardtop, Special Edition two-door hardtop, or convertible.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The base model was the Challenger with either an inline-6 or V8 engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The Special Edition hardtop, available on either the base Challenger or on the R/T, added a number of appearance, convenience, and comfort features.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The standard engine on the base model was a 225 cu in (3.7 L) Straight-6.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The standard engine on the higher trim models was a 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 with a 2-barrel carburetor.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] A 4-speed manual was optional on all engines except the 225 cu in (3.7 L) Inline-6 and the 2-barrel 383 cu in (6.3 L) V8.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The performance model was the **Challenger R/T** (Road/Track), with a 383 cu in (6.3 L) "Magnum" V8, rated at 335 hp (250 kW); 300 hp (224 kW) for 1971, due to a drop in compression.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The standard transmission was a 3-speed manual.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The R/T was available in either the hardtop or convertible.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The Challenger R/T came with a Rallye instrument cluster that included a 150 mph (240 km/h) speedometer, an 8,000 rpm tachometer and an oil pressure gauge.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The shaker hood scoop was not available after 1971.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] A mid-year introduction was the low-priced **Challenger Deputy**, a coupe with fixed rear quarter windows lacking some of the base car's trim with fixed rear side glass as the most notable identifier.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] This model was named after a "sheriff-type" character that was featured in television commercials by Dodge at the time.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] A special model only available for the 1970 model year was the **Challenger T/A** (Trans Am) racing homologation car.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] To race in the Sports Car Club of America's Trans American Sedan Championship Trans Am, Dodge built a street version of its race car (just like Plymouth with its Plymouth 'Cuda AAR) which it called the Dodge Challenger T/A (Trans Am).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Although the race cars ran a destroked 303 cu in (5.0 L) version of the modified 340, street versions took the 340 and added a trio of two-barrel carburetors atop an aluminum intake manifold, creating the 340 **Six Pack**.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Dodge rated the engine at 290 hp (216 kW), only 15 hp (11 kW) more than the original 340 engine (which also had the same rating as the Camaro Z/28 and Ford Boss 302 Mustang).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Air came in through a suitcase-sized air scoop molded into the pinned-down, hinged matte-black fiberglass hood.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] A low-restriction dual-outlet exhaust ran to the stock muffler location, then reversed direction to exit in chrome-tipped "megaphone" outlets in front of the rear wheels.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Options included a TorqueFlite automatic or pistol-grip Hurst-shifted four-speed transmission, 3.55:1 or 3.90:1 gear ratios, as well as manual or power steering.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The special Rallye suspension used heavy-duty parts and increased the rate of the rear springs.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The T/A was one of the first U.S. muscle cars to fit different size tires at the front and rear: E60x15 Goodyear Polyglas in the front, and G60x15 on the rear axle.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The modified camber elevated the tail enough to clear the rear tires and its side exhaust outlets.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Thick dual side stripes, bold ID graphics, a fiberglass ducktail rear spoiler, and a fiberglass front spoiler were also included.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The interior was identical to other Challengers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Dodge contracted Ray Caldwell's Autodynamics in Marblehead, Massachusetts to run the factory Trans-Am team.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Sam Posey drove the No.77 "sub-lime" painted car that Caldwell's team built from a car taken off a local dealer's showroom floor.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] When the No.76 was completed mid-season from a chassis provided by Dan Gurney's All American Racers, Posey alternated between the two.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Both cars ran the final two races, with Posey in the No.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Ronnie Bucknum drove the No.76 at Seattle, Washington, and Tony Adamowicz drove it at Riverside, California.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The Challenger T/A's scored a few top-three finishes, but lack of a development budget and the short-lived Keith Black built race engines led to Dodge leaving the series at season's end.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The street version suffered from severe understeer in fast corners, largely due to the smaller front tires.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] A 1971 model using the 340 engine with a 4-barrel carburetor was planned and appeared in advertising, but was not produced since Dodge had withdrawn from the race series.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] For the 1971 model year the **Challenger Coupe** became the entry-level model, with either a straight-six or V8 engine.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Like the Challenger Deputy it replaced, it had fixed rear quarter windows and a basic black steering wheel with horn button.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] For the 1972 model year, the options lists (both for performance and appearance/convenience items) had been drastically cut back.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The convertible version (though a sunroof was made available), most interior upgrade options (in particular leather seats), comfort/convenience items (in particular power windows and power seats), and all the big-block engine options were gone.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The R/T series was replaced by the Challenger Rallye series.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The Rallye model featured four simulated vents on the front fenders, from which exited matte black strobe tape stripes.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Engine choices were down to three: the 225 cu in (3.7 L) slant-6, 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8, and a 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8 that was equipped with a 4-barrel carburetor, dual exhausts, as well as a performance-oriented camshaft and heads.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] All three engines were detuned to lower compression ratios to run on lead-free gasoline, and the horsepower ratings were lowered to reflect the more accurate Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) net horsepower calculations.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Each engine could be mated to a 3-speed manual or automatic transmission, while the 340 could also be equipped with a 4-speed manual if so ordered.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The performance axle ratios were also gone except for a 3.55 sure grip which could only be had with the 340 and the heavy-duty suspension.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The 1972 models also received a new grille that extended beneath the front bumper, as well as new rear tail-lights.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Toward the end of the 1971 model year, a few convertibles were made with the 1972 front end (grille, lights, etc.) and rear end (tail lights and their panel).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The only way to ascertain these 1972 Challenger convertibles is to look at its fender tag.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] On the code line which gives the dealer order number, that number will start with an "R", which designates "Special Meaning" (in this case, a TV 'special promotions' car).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The 1972 grille and tail-light arrangement were carried over for the 1973 (and 1974) model years, and the mandatory 5 mph bumpers were added.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] While the 225 cu in (3.7 L) six-cylinder engine was dropped, (leaving just the two V8s), all option lists otherwise were carry-overs from 1972.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] For 1974, the 340 cu in (5.6 L) engine was replaced by a 360 cu in (5.9 L) version offering 245 hp (183 kW), but the pony car market had fallen off and production of Challengers ceased in late April 1974.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Although the body style remained the same throughout the Challenger's five-year run, there were two notable changes to the front grille.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The 1971 models had a "split" grille, while 1972 introduced a design that extended the grille (nicknamed the "sad-mouth") beneath the front bumper.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] With this change to the front end, 1972 through 1974 models had little to no variation.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The 1974 cars had larger rear bumper guards to meet the (new for 1974 and on) rear 5 mph (8.0 km/h) rear impact law.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] These changes were made to meet U.S. regulations regarding crash test safety.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The 1970 taillights went all the way across the back of the car, with the backup light in the middle.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] In 1971, the backup lights were on the left and right instead of the middle.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The taillight array also changed for 1972 onwards, with the Challenger now having four individual rectangular lamps.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Although few mourned the end of the E-body models, the passage of time has created legends and highlighted the unique personalities of both the Challenger and the Barracuda.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] With a low total production, as well as low survivability over the years, any *Challenger* is worth a substantial amount of money.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] In a historic review, the editors of *Edmunds Inside Line* ranked these models as: 1970 was a "great" year, 1971 was a "good" one, and then "three progressively lousier ones" (1972–1974).
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Dodge Challengers were mainly produced for the U.S. and Canadian markets.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Chrysler officially sold Challengers to Switzerland through AMAG Automobil- und Motoren AG in Schinznach-Bad, near Zürich.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Only a few cars were shipped overseas each year to AMAG.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] They did the final assembly of the Challengers and converted them to Swiss specifications.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] There are few AMAG cars still in existence.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] From a collector's point of view, these cars are very desirable.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Today, fewer than five Swiss Challengers are known to exist in North America.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Chrysler exported Dodge Challengers officially to France as well through their Chrysler France Simca operation, since Ford sold the Mustang in France successfully in small numbers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] However, only a few Challengers were exported and Chrysler finally gave up the idea of selling them in France.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The SAE gross horsepower ratings were determined testing the engine with no accessories, no air cleaner, or open dyno headers.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] In 1971 compression ratios were reduced in performance engines, except the 426 cu in (7.0 L) and the high performance 440 cu in (7.2 L), to accommodate regular gasoline.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] 1971 was the last year for the 426 cu in (7.0 L) Hemi.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The Challenger was introduced to the SCCA Trans Am Series in 1970.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] Two factory-backed cars were prepared by Ray Caldwell's Autodynamics and driven by Sam Posey and Tony Adamowicz.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The No.77 car was built at Autodynamics from a street Challenger T/A that was taken from a local dealer showroom.
[src:dodge-challenger-1970/dodge-challenger-1970] The No.76 chassis arrived mid-season from Dan Gurney's All-American Racers and was completed by Autodynamics.
